<example xml:id="sample-MX3"><title>MX3</title>
<statement>
    Use a matrix inverse to solve the following matrix-vector equation.
    <me>\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
        1&amp; 2&amp; 1\\
        0&amp; 0&amp; 2\\
        1&amp; 1&amp; 1\\
        \end{array}\right] \vec{v} = \left[\begin{array}{c}4\\ -2 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]</me>
</statement>
<solution>
    Using the techniques from section <xref ref="MX3"></xref>, and letting <m>M = \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
        1&amp; 2&amp; 1\\
        0&amp; 0&amp; 2\\
        1&amp; 1&amp; 1\\
        \end{array}\right]</m>, we find <m>M^{-1} = \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
        -1&amp; -1/2&amp; 2\\
        1&amp; 0&amp; -1\\
        0&amp; 1/2&amp; 0\\
        \end{array}\right]</m>.
    Our equation can be written as <m>M\vec{v} = \left[\begin{array}{c}4\\ -2 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]</m>, and may therefore be solved via 
    <me>\vec{v} = I\vec{v} = M^{-1}M\vec{v} = M^{-1}\left[\begin{array}{c}4\\ -2 \\ 2 \end{array}\right] = 
        \left[\begin{array}{c}1\\ 2 \\ -1 \end{array}\right]</me>
</solution>
</example>